Wash and dry produce.

Trim and peel @carrots{6%ounce} using a #peeler{}, shave carrot lengthwise into
ribbons, rotating as you go, until you get to the core. Discard core. Halve,
core, and dice @apple{1} into ½-inch pieces. Halve, peel, and thinly slice
@yellow onion{1}. Finely chop @parsley{1/4%ounce}. Roughly chop
@walnuts{1/2%ounce}.

In a #large bowl{}, toss @mixed greens{2%ounce} with carrot ribbons and apple.
Set aside.

Heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tablespoon} in a large, preferably
#nonstick pan{} over medium-high heat. Add onion and cook,
stirring occasionally, until browned and softened, ~{8-10%minutes}.

Add 2 tsp @white wine vinegar{5%teaspoon}, ¼ tsp @dried thyme{1%teaspoon},
@sugar{1%teaspoon}, and a splash of water (for 4 servings, use 4 tsp vinegar,
½ tsp thyme, and 2 tsp sugar). Cook, stirring occasionally, until caramelized
and jammy, ~{2-3%minutes}.

> TIP: If pan seems dry, stir in more splashes of water.

Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Turn off heat; transfer to a #small bowl{}. Wipe out pan.

Pat @chicken cutlets{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}. Season all over with
salt and pepper.

Heat a drizzle of oil in pan used for onion over medium-high heat. Add chicken
and cook until browned and cooked through, ~{3-5%minutes} per side.

Remove from pan and set aside. Cover to keep warm.

Return caramelized onion to pan. Stir in @chicken stock concentrate{1},
½ tsp vinegar (1 tsp for 4 servings), and ¼ cup water (1⁄3 cup for 4). Cook,
stirring, until combined and thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Remove pan from heat. Stir in @crème fraîche{2%tablespoon},
@cream cheese{2%tablespoon}, half the parsley, and 1 tbsp @butter{1%tablespoon}
(2 tbsp for 4) until combined.

> TIP: If sauce seems too thick, stir in water 1 tbsp at a time.

Drizzle @honey Dijon dressing{1.5%ounce} over salad; toss to coat.

Divide chicken and salad between plates. Pour sauce over chicken. Top salad
with walnuts. Garnish everything with remaining parsley and serve.